    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok that makes sense. so with mechanical tension, you mentioned the micro-tears in the fibers. could you go a bit deeper into the cellular level? like what's actually happening inside the muscle cell when that tension is applied to trigger the growth response?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When mechanical tension is applied, you're essentially putting the muscle fibers under a heavy, demanding load. Inside the muscle cell, this tension translates into physical strain on the contractile proteins, primarily the actin and myosin filaments. If the tension is high enough, these structures get stressed, leading to microscopic tears—the very definition of muscle damage. These tears are the signal the body uses to initiate repair and growth.",
      "source": "target",
